Christopher Milton Mathew Franco Received: 13 January 2021 / Accepted: 8 February 2021 / Published online: 4 March 2021 (cid:2) The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Nature Switzerland AG part of Springer Nature 2021 Abstract An endophytic actinobacterium, strain CAP215T was isolated from the root sample of a native pine tree (Callitris preissii), Adelaide, South Australia. This strain was a Gram stain-positive, aerobic actinobacterium with well-developed sub- strate mycelia. It produced spiral chains of spores. The closest phylogenetic members which shared the highest 16S rRNA gene sequence similarity were Streptomyces marinus DSM 41968T, Streptomyces haliclonae DSM 41970T and Streptomyces karpasien- sis K413T at 98.2%, 98.0% and 97.9%, respectively. The major cellular fatty acid of this strain was anteiso- C15:0 and major menaquinone was MK-9(H4). Polar lipids contained The GenBank/EMBL/DDBJ accession number for the 16S rRNA gene sequence of strain CAP215T is GU434243. The GenBank/EMBL/DDBJ accession number for the draft genome of strain CAP215T is JACBXA000000000. Chemotaxo- nomic data conﬁrmed strain CAP215T belonged to the genus Streptomyces. Genome of strain CAP215T was 6.65 Mb with 69.8% DNA G ? C content and contains 5992 coding sequences (CDS). Biosynthesis Genes Clusters (BGCs) comprised post-translationally modiﬁed peptides (RiPPs) cluster, genes encoding enzyme relating to antibiotic production; acti- norhodin, surfactin and tetracenomycin. Genome this strain identiﬁed genes encoding mining of proteins relating to plant growth promotion such as pyrophosphatase, ectoine synthase, superoxide dis- mutase and siderophore production; penibactin and beneﬁcial desferrioxamine E. Genes enzymes; amylase, b-xylosidase, chitinase, lipase and protease were detected. The genome of this strain contained genes encoding enzymes degrading xeno- 2,4-dichlorophenol biotic 6-monooxygenase, nitroreductase and epoxide hydro- lase. Also, genes encoding squalene, hopene and betacarotenoid production were observed. Digital DNA–DNA (dDDH) hybridization, Average Nucleo- tide Identity BLAST (ANIb), ANI-MUMmer (ANIm) between strain CAP215T and S. marinus DSM 41968T were 25.4 %, 82% and 86.4%, respectively. The data on the genotypic and phenotypic characteristics and genome analysis recognized the differentiation of strain CAP215T with the closest species with valid names. The name Streptomyces albidus sp. nov. was

proposed for which the type strain is CAP215T (= DSM 42025T = NRRL B-24815T). Keywords Actinobacterium (cid:2) Endophyte (cid:2) Genome mining (cid:2) MRSA The genus Streptomyces belonging to the Family Streptomycetaceae is aerobic, Gram-stain positive with high guanine and cytosine in their DNA. Colonies are made up of branched substrate and aerial mycelia containing chains of spores. The cell-wall contains LL- diaminopimelic acid (LL-DAP). Fatty acids are of iso- and anteiso types, and they have phospholipid type II phos- which phatidylethanolamine, and phosphatidylinositol mannosides (Ka¨mpfer 2012). The predominant menaquinones are MK9-(H6) and MK9-(H8). They are a major group of the phylum Actinobacteria and have been discovered from a range of environments such as soil, compost, fresh water, marine sediments, sponge, deserts, hot springs and plant samples, though the majority were isolated from soil. Recently, many endophytic isolates of Strepto- myces have been reported as novel species (https:// lpsn.dsmz.de/genus/Streptomyces) (Parte et al. 2020). Streptomyces spp. are well known antibiotic producers yielding more than 70 percent of currently known antibiotics. Also, there are many reports of their application to crop plants as plant growth promoters, phytohormone producers and inducers of systemic resistance (Conn et al. 2008; Ka¨mpfer 2012). Strain CAP215T was previously obtained from a study which focused on the biodiversity of endophytic actinobac- teria from Australian native trees and screened for antimicrobial activity (Kaewkla and Franco 2013). The objective of this study was to identify Strepto- myces strain CAP215T as a novel species and to mine its genome to predict genes relating to BGCs by using ‘‘antiSMASH’’ and in silico approach.

Streptomyces albidus sp. nov. (cid:2) Isolation and puriﬁcation of actinobacteria The root of a native pine tree (Callitris preissii) the Bedford Park campus of Flinders growing at University, Adelaide, South Australia (35.024636 S 138.571604 E) was used for isolation. The root sample was surface sterilized as described by Kaewkla and Franco (2013). Crushed surface-sterilised root tissue was placed onto VL70 medium with pectin (0.5 mM) as sole carbon and energy source and solidiﬁed with 0.8% gellan gum. The medium was supplemented with 20 lg ml-1 nalidixic acid and 100 U ml-1 nystatin to inhibit most bacterial and fungal contam- ination, respectively. A small sealable plastic box which was lined with wet paper towels was used to keep plates to preserve the moisture levels during the long incubation times and incubated at 27 (cid:3)C for up to 16 weeks. Isolation plates were observed weekly and the emergence time of each colony was recorded. Actinobacterial colonies were puriﬁed by streaking onto half-strength potato dextrose agar (HPDA, Difco) plates. Pure cultures were kept on HPDA slants at 4 (cid:3)C, and in 20% glycerol at - 80 (cid:3)C for further study (Schoenborn et al. 2004; Kaewkla and Franco 2013). Phylogenetic analysis of 16S rRNA gene

Genomic DNA of strain CAP215T was extracted by using GenEluteTM (Sigma, St Louis, USA). The 16S rRNA gene was ampliﬁed and sequenced following the protocol described previously (Kaewkla and Franco 2013). The sequences of the 16S rRNA genes of strain CAP215T and representatives of closely related validly described strains of the genus Strepto- myces available from GenBank/EMBL were retrieved by using CLUSTAL X (Thompson et al. 1997), and were analyzed using EzTaxon-e server (Yoon et al. 2017). The phylogenetic trees were constructed by the neighbor-joining analysis and maximum likelihood algorithms using the software package MEGA version X (Kumar et al. 2018) with Actinomyces haliotis JCM 18848T as the outgroup. The neighbor joining algo- rithm (Saitou and Nei 1987) was calculated according to the Tajima–Nei method (Tajima and Nei 1984). The Kimura 2-parameter model (Kimura 1980) was applied in the maximum likelihood approach by using (Nearest-Neighbor- the ML Heuristic Method Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (2021) 114:539–551 Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (2021) 114:539–551 Interchange, NNI). The topology of the tree was evaluated by performing a bootstrap analysis (Felsen- stein 1985) based on 1000 replications. Sequencing, assembly and annotation of genome

Genomic DNA was extracted using GenEluteTM (Sigma, St Louis, USA) and PCR library was constructed by using a short insert size library. The genome of this strain was sequenced using an Illumina Hiseq X-ten platform (Illumina) (2 9 150 bp paired- end reads) at the Beijing Genome Institute (BGI), Hongkong. Unicycler (0.4.8) was applied for de novo assembly of the reads (Wick et al. 2017). The genome of strain CAP215T was annotated by using Prokka version 1.14.5 (Seemann 2014) and the NCBI Prokaryotic Genome Annotation Pipeline (PGAP) (Tatusova et al. 2016).

The phylogenetic tree of genome of strain CAP215T and related taxa was constructed by using the Type (strain) Genome Server (TYGS) (Meier-Kolthoff et al. 2013; Meier-Kolthoff and Go¨ker 2019). The tree inferred with FastME 2.1.6.1 (Lefort et al. 2015) from Genome BLAST Distance Phylogeny (GBDP) dis- tances calculated from genome sequences. The branch lengths were scaled in terms of GBDP distance formula d4. The genome comparison study of strain CAP215T was carried out with the closest type strain. There was only one genome of the closest type strain; Streptomyces marinus DSM 41968T which is available in the public database. Strain CAP215T and S. marinus DSM 41968T were evaluated for the average nucleo- tide identity (ANI) values with pairwise genome alignment by using ANI-BLAST (ANIb) and ANI- MUMmer (ANIm) algorithms within the JSpeciesWS web service (Richter and Rossello´-Mo´ra 2009; Richter et al. 2016). The Genome-to-Genome Distance calcu- lator (GGDC 2.1; BLAST ? method) applying for- mula 2 (identities/HSP length) was used to calculate digital DNA–DNA hybridization (dDDH) values of strain CAP215T with other closest type strains (Meier- Kolthoff et al. 2013).

The isomer of diaminopimelic acid was detected by Thin Layer Chromatography (TLC) using the method of Bousﬁeld et al. (1985) and whole-cell sugar was analyzed by the TLC method of Hasegawa et al. (1983). The phospholipid pattern was determined as described by Minnikin et al. (1984) and Komagata and Suzuki (1987) using 5% ethanolic molybdophosphoric lipids, and other sprays acid for detection of all including Dragendorff, periodate-Schiff, a-naphthol, ninhydrin and molybdenum blue reagents were also used to detect Isoprenoid quinones were extracted and puriﬁed by using the method of Minnikin et al. (1984) with analysis of the samples by reverse phase LC-MS employing UV detection and electrospray mass spectrometry (ESI) as described previously (Kaewkla and Franco 2019). Whole-cell fatty acids of strain CAP215T and the three closest Streptomyces type strains were analyzed by growing cultures for 7 days at 27 (cid:3)C in Tryptic Soy Broth (Oxoid) in an Erlenmeyer ﬂask on a rotary shaker at 150 rpm and cells were harvested typically by centrifugation. Washed cells (100 mg) were saponiﬁed, methylated and extracted and the fatty acid methyl esters (FAMEs) were determined by following the protocols described by Microbial Iden- tiﬁcation Inc (MIDI) (Sasser 2001). The Sherlock ACTIN6 software version 6.2B was used for analysis.

Cultural characteristics of strain CAP215T and the three closest type strains were observed on 8 different media: ISP 2, ISP 3, ISP 4, ISP 5, ISP 7 (ISP, International Streptomyces Project) (Shirling and Gottlieb 1966; Atlas and Park 1993), Bennett’s agar, (HPDA) and half-strength Potato Dextrose agar Nutrient agar (NA) (Atlas and Park 1993). Methuen handbook of colour was used for colour determination (Kornerup and Wanscher 1978). The visualization of cells and spores after 10 days of incubation at 27 (cid:3)C on HPDA applied Scanning Electron Microscopy (The Philips XL30 Field Emission Scanning Electron Microscope) at Adelaide Microscopy, Adelaide University, Adelaide, South Australia. The sample preparation was carried out according to previous study (Kaewkla and Franco 2019). Physiological and biochemical characteristics Physiological and biochemical characteristics of strain CAP215T and the three closest type strains, S. marinus DSM 41968T, S. haliclonae DSM 41970T and S. karpasiensis K413T, were studied in a side-by-side comparison. Acid production from eighteen carbohy- drates and decomposition of esculin, L-tyrosine, and urea were assessed according to the methods of Gordon et al. (1974). Hydrolysis of starch, assimila- tion of seven organic acids, utilization of four phenolic compounds as sole carbon source and catalase production were described by Kurup and Schmitt (1973). Growth at different temperatures (4, 15, 27, 37, 45 and 55 (cid:3)C), pH between 4 and 10 (in 1 pH unit intervals), and NaCl concentrations (1, 3, 5, 10, 15 and 20%, w/v) were evaluated after incubation at 27 (cid:3)C for 10–14 days on ISP 2 medium (Kurup and Schmitt 1973). Antimicrobial assay against MRSA

Bacteria used for the antibacterial bioassay were two resistant strains of Gram negative bacteria: Pseu- domonas aeruginosa 06348315 and Enterobacter cloacae 06351089; a sensitive strain and a resistant strain of Gram positive bacteria; Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 29213 and Methicillin resistant Sta- phylococcus aureus (MRSA) 03120385 and one yeast; Candida albicans ATCC 10231. All test microorgan- isms were obtained from the Clinical Microbiology Department, the Flinders University, South Australia. Strains CAP215T was cultured on HPDA for 7 days. Two loops of cells or spores were cultured in 50 ml of seed medium, ISP 2 medium (Composition per litre; malt extract 10 g, glucose 4 g, yeast extract 4 g) in 250 ml bafﬂed Erlenmeyer ﬂasks and incubated at 27 (cid:3)C with shaking at 150 rpm for 3 days. Solid culture containing rice as substrate was used for antibiotics production. Rice medium contained basmati rice 20 g, 5 ml of LF 42 medium containing 1X HO-LE solution and 15 ml of RO water in 250 ml conical ﬂask. LF 42 medium contained 5 g yeast extract, 5 g peptone, 5 g soya ﬂour, 4 ml glycerol, 2 g soluble starch, 2 g CaCO3, 2 g NaCl, 0.5 g K2HPO4 and 0.5 g MgSO4.7- H20 per litre RO water. HO-LE solution (1000X) contained (g/L) H3BO3 2.85, MnCl2(cid:2)4H2O 1.8, Sodium tartrate 1.77, FeSO4(cid:2)7H2O 1.36, CoCl2(cid:2)6H2O 0.04, CuCl2(cid:2)2H2O 0.027, Na2MoO4(cid:2)2H2O 0.025 and

ZnCl2 0.020. Rice medium was autoclaved at 121 (cid:3)C and then inoculated with 1 ml of three days old inoculum and mixed thoroughly. They were then incubated at 27 (cid:3)C for 5 days and the experiment was done in triplicate. Sterile RO water was added when the culture started to dry until 1 mm of water could be seen at the bottom of the ﬂasks. After ﬁve days of fermentation, 60 mL of methanol was added to each ﬂask and mixed by shaking on a shaker at 150 rpm for 3 h at 27 (cid:3)C. The methanol extracts were collected by centrifugation at 8000 rpm for 10 min at 4 (cid:3)C. The methanol extract was evaporated by using a rotary evaporator and residual water was freeze dried and kept at - 20 (cid:3)C until the bioassay could be performed. Antibiotic assay medium (AAM: Oxoid) was used for the antibacterial activity assay. Test bacteria were grown in tryptone soy broth (TSB: Oxoid) at 37 (cid:3)C by shaking at 150 rpm for 18 h. The growth of bacteria was assessed by measuring the optical density (OD) using a spectrophotometer at 600 nm and the OD was adjusted to 0.2. The test organisms were added to AAM medium at 45 (cid:3)C at the ratio of 4% inoculum and 30 ml was eventually poured into a 9 cm petri dish. The AAM agar which was seeded with the test organisms was cut using a 6 mm cork borer to make wells (nine wells per plate). Dried methanol extract (10 mg ml-1) was dissolved with 60% methanol and ﬁfty microliters were added into each well. The test plates were incubated at 37 (cid:3)C for 18–24 h and the antibacterial activity was assessed by measuring the inhibition zone. The method used for anti-yeast bioassay was similar to the antibacterial assay but Sabouraud dext

test plates were incubated at 37 (cid:3)C for 18–24 h and the antibacterial activity was assessed by measuring the inhibition zone. The method used for anti-yeast bioassay was similar to the antibacterial assay but Sabouraud dextrose broth and Sabouraud dextrose agar (Oxoid) at pH 6.0 were used instead of TSB and AAM agar for seed medium and antibiotic assays, respectively. Moreover, the incubation temperature and the incubation times were 27 (cid:3)C and 24 h. Vancomycin (500 ug/ml), colistin (500 lg/ml), amphotericin B (250 ug/ml) were used as standard antibiotics against Gram positive bacteria, Gram negative bacteria and yeast, respectively. 60% metha- nol was used as a negative control.

Genome of strain CAP215T was mined for genes relating to antibiotics and enzyme production, biore- mediation, and plant growth promotion. Secondary (anti-SMASH) version metabolite Analysis Shell Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (2021) 114:539–551 Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (2021) 114:539–551 5.1.0 (Blin et al. 2019) was applied to reveal biosyn- thetic gene clusters (BGCs). In silico approach was also applied to scan for genes relating to these properties. The gene products and the closest similar- ity of microorganisms were obtained by applying blastp on the Uniprot database with matrix; blosum62 (https://www.uniprot.org/blast; The UniProt Consor- tium 2019). Isolation of strain CAP215T A Streptomyces-like colony arose as a small cream colony from the root tissue of a native pine tree after incubation for 7 weeks on VL-70 medium supple- mented with pectin. This culture was designated as strain CAP215T. Phylogenetic analysis of 16S rRNA gene

Based on 16S rRNA gene analysis, the closest neighbor of strain CAP215T was Streptomyces mar- inus DSM 41968T with a high bootstrap number at 60 and 36 on neighbor joining and maximum likelihood trees, respectively. This type strain shared the highest 16S rRNA gene similarity with CAP215T at 98.2%. The similarity with other type strains was as follows: Streptomyces haliclonae DSM 41970T (98%), Strep- tomyces ovatisporus S4702T (98%) and Streptomyces karpasiensis K413T (97.9%). Strain CAP215T posi- tioned in the same clade as S. marinus DSM 41968T and in the same cluster with S. haliclonae DSM 41970T and S. karpasiensis K413T. Streptomyces ovatisporus S4702T positioned into a different cluster with strain CAP215T on both trees (Fig. 1 and Fig S1 available online). Thus, S. marinus DSM 41968T, S. haliclonae DSM 41970T and S. karpasiensis K413T were selected for a comparative study with strain CAP215T. The draft genome assembly of strain CAP215T has been submitted to GenBank as accession number JACBXA000000000. The draft genome sequence of strain CAP215T was 6.65 Mb and a DNA G ? C

content determined by in silico genome sequencing as 69.8 mol%. The draft genomic document of the strain CAP215T and S. marinus DSM 41968T was described in Table 1. The genome analysis showed the ANIb and ANIm values of the draft genome between strain CAP215T and its closest species, S. marinus DSM 41968T at 82.0 and 86.4%, respectively. The dDDH value between the genome of strain CAP215T and the closest type strain; S. marinus DSM 41968T was 25.4 [ct 23.1–27.9] and with other strains, Streptomyces durbertensis DSM 104538T, Streptomyces cacaoi NBRC 12748T at 22.7 [ct 20.4–25.1] and 22.7 [ct 20.4–25.1], respectively, of which the latter shared a 16S rRNA gene sequence similarity less than 96.0%. The phylogenetic tree based on TYGS revealed the relationship between strain CAP215T and the related type strains. The result clearly showed that strain CAP215T was positioned at the same node with the closest type strain, S. marinus DSM 41968T and well- deﬁned as different species with other related mem- bers of genus Streptomyces (Fig. 2).

Kim et al. (2014) stated that a 16S rRNA gene similarity lower than 98.65% cutoff should delineate different species. Therefore, strain CAP215T which shared a highest 16S rRNA gene similarity at 98.2% with the closest type strain, S. marinus DSM 41968T could be distinguished from other valid species of the genus Streptomyces. In addition, according to the report of Richter and Rossello´-Mo´ra (2009), an ANI values lower than the 95–96% cut off should delineate different species. Also, a dDDH value which lower than the threshold of 70% was used to deﬁne species level (Meier-Kolthoff et al. 2013; Chun et al. 2018). Based on the genotypic data, strain CAP215T could be distinguished from other Streptomyces valid names. LL-DAP was detected in the whole-cell of strain CAP215T. The whole-cell sugar contained galactose, glucose and ribose. Diphosphatidylglycerol (DPG), phosphatidylethanolamine (PE), phosphatidylinositol dimannoside (PIDM), Phosphatidylinositol (PI), Phos- phatidylmethylethanolamine (PME), three unknown phophoglycolipids and one unknown glycolipid were detected (Supplementary Fig. S2) which corresponded to phospholipid type II (Lechevalier et al. 1977). Furthermore, S. marinus DSM 41968T could use pyridine but strain CAP215T could not. Based on the results of the chemotaxonomic, physiological and biochemical data, strain CAP215T was determined to be different from its closest species of the genus Streptomyces. Strain CAP215T produced bioactive compounds which strongly inhibited S. aureus ATCC 29213 and MRSA 03120385. This strain did not show activity to inhibit resistant strains of Gram negative bacteria, P. aeruginosa 06348315 and E. cloacae 06351089 and yeast; Candida albicans ATCC 10231 (Table 4). S. marinus DSM 41968T produced aranciamycin which inhibited Gram positive bacteria Mycobacterium bovis and Bacillus subtilis, antibiotic SM 173B and three novel anthracycline analogues (JBIR-29, -30, -43) and S. haliclonae DSM 41970T produced griseoviridin and viridogrisein which is active against Brachyspira hyodysenteriae, a Gram negative spirochete causing swine dysentery (Asano and Adachi 2006).

Based on the result of the gene cluster prediction derived from the ‘antiSMASH’ database, strain CAP215T contained genes which shared similarity with four known pathways at 40% or higher; non- ribosomal peptide synthetase cluster (NRPS), lan- thipeptide cluster, post-translationally modiﬁed pep- tides (RiPPs) and other types including geosmin, two siderophores and ectoine (Table 5). Strain CAP215T contained a gene cluster with 75% similarity with bingicin alpha and bingicin beta belonging to a lanthipeptide cluster group. It was reported that a ribosomally synthesized and post-translationally mod- iﬁed peptides (RiPPs) presenting a variety of biolog- ical activities such as antimicrobial and antiallodynic activities (Repka et al. 2017). According to Repka et al. (2017), microorganisms containing RiPPs and lanthipeptide gene clusters are likely to produce novel substances such as an antibiotic that could inhibit MRSA. The ﬁnding of this gene was inline with the result of anti-MRSA assay in vitro of strain CAP215T. The result of in silico approach showed that strain CAP215T contained two genes relating to acti- norhodin (55.7 and 77.1% similarity), benzoisochro- strain contained manequinone surfactin synthase thioesterase subunit encoding sur- factin production (71.4% similarity), a lipopeptide which possesses antibacterial, antiviral, antifungal, anti-mycoplasma and hemolytic activities (Singh and Cameotra 2004). In addition, this strain comprised two gene clusters relating to tetracenomycin production (55.2 and 59.3%), an anthracycline antitumor via polyketide pathway (Shen and Hutchinson 1993) (Supplementary Table S2).

According to the report of Khan et al. (2011), the closest strains, S. marinus DSM 41968T contained polyketide synthase type I (PKSI), PKSII and NRPS which shared similarity with these known cluster at 57–76%, 85% and 43–74%, respectively. This strain produced three novel anthracycline analogues (JBIR- 29, -30, -43) (Khan et al. 2011). Based on the result of genes encoding antibiotics production sharing low similarity with known genes or known clusters, strain CAP215T had a possibility to produce novel antibi- otics or bioactive compounds. Strain CAP215T will be investigated to elucidate its antibiotics structures in the future. Catalase was positive for all strains. All strains could produce acid from fructose, galactose, glucose, maltose, mannose, mannitol, sucrose, trehalose, xylose but not cellulose and sorbitol. All strains could assimilate citrate, acetate and malate but not benzoate. They could hydrolyze esculin and starch. They could not use toluene, phenol and benzene as sole carbon source. All strains could grow at 27 (cid:3)C and 37 (cid:3)C and between pH 7 and pH 10. It was possible that strain Cap215T may produce a novel siderophore which beneﬁts plants to chelate iron. The genome of strain CAP215T was scanned for genes relating to enzyme production, bioremediation, plant growth promotion and other interesting activi- ties. For plant growth promoting properties, the results revealed that this strain contained a range of genes encoding for drought tolerance, stress protein, iron Hydrolysis of: L-tyrosine Urea Use of phenolic compounds

uptake protein, and siderophore production (Supple- mentary Table S2). For drought or salt tolerance, genes encoding ectoine, betaine transport, osmopro- tectant transport system ATP-binding protein and sodium:solute symporter which related to osmoregu- lation were detected in strain CAP215T (Horn et al. 2006). Also, there were genes encoding three proteins which related to stress response including, superoxide dismutase and salicylate synthase which is responsible Table 5 The distribution of BGCs of Streptomyces albidus CAP215T based on ‘‘antiSMASH’’ for salicylic acid production associated with System- atic Induced Resistance (SAR) (Conn et al. 2008). Strain CAP215T contained genes relating to antioxi- dants; deaminated glutathione amidase and glu- tathione hydrolase. According to Wang et al. (2019) Streptomyces chartreusis WZS021 supported the growth of sugarcane in salt stress conditions contain- ing superoxide dismutase and glycine betaine trans- porter. In addition, strain CAP215T comprised genes relating to siderophore production, desferrioxamine E. Strain CAP215T contained three genes encoding alkaline phosphatase D, dITP/XTP pyrophosphatase and inorganic pyrophosphatase which can solubilize inorganic phosphate in soil and support plants to uptake solubilized phosphate.

Many genes encoding beneﬁcial enzymes were detected in strain CAP215T which can be applied in industry. There were three types of enzymes which could degrade hemicellulose, polysaccharide or plant residue; alpha-N-arabinofuranosidase, amylase and b- xylosidase. Genes encoding chitinase was also detected in this strain. Also, this strain contained lipase and many types of proteases. Gene encoding streptogrisin C of strain CAP215T shared gene sim- ilarity only 79.8% with the known genes, which was this likely to be a novel enzyme. Furthermore, strain contained biosynthesis genes encoding valuable compounds; squalene and cardiolipin. Squalene has an all-trans polyene originally discovered from shark liver oil. This compound was also found in bacteria and archaea which beneﬁts as anticancer, antioxidant and skin care. Fontana et al. (2001) reported biosyn- thesis of squalene via the methylerythritol phosphate pathway in a Streptomyces sp. isolated from a marine sediment.

Many genes encoding enzymes which have a vital role in bioremediation were also detected. This strain contained nine important hydrocarbon degradation genes encoding enzyme; alkanesulfonate monooxy- genase, 2,4-dichlorophenol 6-monooxygenase, glu- tathione-independent formaldehyde dehydrogenase, 2-polyprenyl-6-methoxyphenol hydroxylase, nitroalk- ane oxidase, nitroreductase, 2-nitropropane dioxyge- nase, salicylaldehyde dehydrogenase and vanillate O-demethylase monooxygenase subunit (Visser et al. 1999). Saadoun et al. (2008) investigated Strepto- myces spp. isolated from hydrocarbon-contaminated soil and studied their capability to grow on diesel fuel as a sole carbon source. The result showed some Streptomyces which showed activity to degrade diesel fuel containing alkane hydroxylase gene (alkB). Many such as nitrofurazone, nitroaromatic compounds nitrobenzene, 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene (TNT) are toxic and mutagenic chemicals. Nitrore- ductases are NAD(P)H-dependent ﬂavoenzymes that reduce the nitro groups of polynitrated aromatic compounds (Rolda´n et al. 2008). According to study of Yang et al. (2019), a nitroreductase-encoded gene from an efﬁcient nitro-reducing bacterium Strepto- myces mirabilis DUT001, containing a nitroreductase- encoded gene was studied. This nitroreductase eny- zyme could reduce multiple nitro compounds and ﬂavins, including antibacterial drug; nitrofurazone, priority pollutants 2,4-dinitrotoluene and 2,4,6-trini- trotoluene. In addition, strain CAP215T comprised genes encoding epoxide hydrolases (EHs) which Most similar biosynthetic gene cluster Similarity

Gene encoding nicotine blue oxidoreductase which related to degrade nicotine was also observed in this strain. In conclusion, strain CAP215T can be differentiated from other species of the genus Streptomyces by phylogenetic tree of genome, and its phenotypic and chemotaxonomic features including ANIb and ANIm values, dDDH. The name Streptomyces albidus sp. nov. is proposed for this novel species. This strain could strongly produce antibiotics to inhibit MRSA 03120385. Genome mining revealed that this strain comprised BGCs encoding to antibiotics production and many genes relating to plant growth promoting, beneﬁcial enzymes which could be used in industry and versatile genes encoding xenobiotic degradation enzyme. Description of Streptomyces albidus sp. nov. Streptomyces albidus (al’bi.dus. L. masc. adj. albidus white, referring to the colour of the colonies).

Gram stain-positive, aerobic, catalase positive. Cells grow between 27 and 37 (cid:3)C but grow well at 27 (cid:3)C. Cells grow between pH 7.0 and 10.0 but grow well between pH 7 and pH 8.0. Cells cannot grow in the presence of 3% (w/v) NaCl. Substrate mycelium develops well on all the media used with white cream color but produces aerial mycelium only on HPDA. This strain produces melanin pigments on ISP 7. The mycelium is extensively branched and forms chains of spiral spores. A rod-shaped spore (0.3 lm diameter 9 2 lm length) is observed. Strain CAP215T produces acid from arabinose, fructose, galactose, fucose, glucose, maltose, mannose, mannitol, myo-inositol, sucrose, rafﬁnose, ribose, trehalose and xylose but not cellulose, methyl-D-glucopyranoside, meso-erythritol and sorbitol. Cells assimilate acetate, malate, and propionate but not tartrate and benzoate. Cells hydrolyze esculin and starch but not toluene, phenol, pyridine and benzene as sole carbon source. Whole- cells contain LL-diaminopimelic acid in its peptido- glycan and galactose, glucose and ribose as whole-cell sugars. Phospholipids are diphosphatidylglycerol

phos- (DPG), (PI), phosphatidylinositol diman- phatidylinositol noside (PIDM) including two unknown glycolipids. MK-9(H4), MK-9(H2) and MK-9(H1) are predominant menaquinones. Major cellular fatty acids are anteiso- iso-C16:0 and iso-C15:0. The DNA G ? C C15:0, content of the type strain is 69.8%. The type strain, CAP215T (= DSM 42025T = NRRL B-24815T), is an endophytic actinobacterium isolated from the root of a native pine tree (Callitris preissii) grown at the Bedford park campus of Flinders University, Ade- laide, South Australia. The GenBank/EMBL/DDBJ accession number for the 16S rRNA gene sequence of strain CAP215T is GU434243. The whole genome shotgun project of strain CAP215T has been deposited at DDBJ/ENA/GenBank under the accession number JACBXA000000000. Strain CAP215T can inhibit MRSA 03120385 and contains genes relating to bioactive compounds belonging to lanthipeptide and post-translationally modiﬁed peptides (RiPPs) clus- ters, biodegradation of xenobiotic compounds, plant growth promotion and useful enzymes.
